# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
<overview>
<p>The Liberator-class cruiser is a Clan refit of the Avatar-class heavy cruiser, one of the Star League Defense Force's principal escort combatants of the twenty-sixth and twenty-seventh centuries. Converted from surviving Avatar hulls that accompanied the Exodus fleet, the Liberator entered Clan service around 3024 following a comprehensive modernization program that replaced the original weapons, armor, and electronics suites with Clan-specification systems. Reclassified from its predecessor's escort role into a multi-role cruiser, the Liberator earned a reputation for reliable and flexible service across a broad range of missions, from deep patrol and convoy escort to planetary assault support and aggressive boarding actions. Several Clans fielded Liberators in their naval formations, and the class saw extensive combat service during the invasion era and beyond, gaining particular respect for its balanced combination of firepower, protection, and operational endurance.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Liberator's broadside batteries mount paired Naval Autocannon/30s alongside heavy and medium Naval Gauss Rifles, supplemented by banks of Class 35 Naval Lasers for sustained engagements. Forward and aft quarter arcs carry Naval Autocannon/20 batteries and Heavy Naval PPCs, giving the vessel credible firepower across all engagement angles. Class 45 Naval Lasers defend the nose while heavier Class 55 Naval Lasers cover the stern and aft quarters. The nose and stern sections feature clusters of Ultra Autocannon/10s for rapid-fire point defense, while LB 20-X Autocannons on the aft flanks provide close-range coverage. Missile support comes from LRM-20 launchers fitted with Artemis IV fire control systems on the forward and aft quarter arcs. ER Large Lasers, ER Small Lasers, and Medium Pulse Lasers form a comprehensive anti-fighter screen distributed across multiple arcs.</p><p>The most significant defensive improvement over the original Avatar configuration is the installation of Ferro-Carbide armor plating, providing nearly fifty percent greater protection without sacrificing the vessel's substantial internal volume. A Lithium-Fusion Battery enables rapid successive jumps, while a Mobile HPG provides independent interstellar communication capability. Thirty aerospace fighters organized into three Stars provide organic combat air patrol, and bay space for ten Elemental battle armor Points supports boarding operations. Six docking collars accommodate a substantial DropShip flotilla. The single one hundred forty-five meter gravity deck supports extended deployments, though crew comfort remains modest for a vessel of this displacement. The design lacks dedicated small craft bays entirely, leaving the Liberator dependent on its DropShip complement and fighter wings for auxiliary transport and reconnaissance tasks.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Constantineau served the Star League Defense Force before joining the Exodus fleet. During Operation KLONDIKE, the vessel operated under Clan Burrock command, securing the Dagda zenith jump point and destroying enemy JumpShip engines to isolate the McMillan Collective. Following Clan Burrock's absorption, the WarShip passed to Clan Star Adder. Clan Snow Raven forces destroyed the Constantineau in the York system in 3068 during a Trial of Possession dispute.</p><p>The Korat served alongside the Black Lion-class battlecruiser Thunderbolt during Operation KLONDIKE, engaging spacefarer forces at Outpost One in the Circe system. The vessel later entered Clan Smoke Jaguar service as flagship of Delta Galaxy. Task Force Serpent destroyed the Korat during the assault on Huntress in 3060.</p><p>The Gauntlet served Clan Jade Falcon as part of the Emerald Talon Naval Assault Star. The vessel defended Ironhold against Clan Steel Viper in late 3069 before being destroyed at Lum in February 3070 during a three-hour engagement defending the last major Jade Falcon Homeworld enclave.</p><p>Two Liberators served Clan Wolf as the Blood Fang and Fuego Lobo following the Refusal War. When Clan Jade Wolf was reabsorbed into Clan Wolf around 3058, both vessels were likely renamed Jerome Winson and Victoria Ward. Both WarShips survived the Jihad and were maintained during the Dark Age through Clan Sea Fox shipyard services, remaining two of only five active WarShips in the Clan Wolf Naval Star by 3145.</p><p>Clan Coyote operated the Spirit in the Sky within Epsilon Galaxy. The vessel escaped the destruction at Tamaron in December 3074 and later destroyed the Blood Spirit WarShip Exsanguine in 3082. By 3085, the vessel was one of only three Coyote WarShips still operational, undergoing repairs at the Kirin Shipyard.</p><p>The Morello presents a chronological anomaly. Listed as a Liberator when the Exodus fleet assembled, this designation predates the Clan-era refit by over two centuries. Whether the Morello was an early prototype conversion or a retroactive classification remains debated.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Avatar-class heavy cruiser entered Star League Defense Force service in 2531 as a replacement for the aging Aegis-class frigate. The design served the SLDF well for over two centuries before being superseded by the Luxor-class in the early twenty-eighth century, with many vessels transferred to reserve fleets or reassigned as training ships.</p><p>The Amaris Civil War proved devastating to the remaining Avatar fleet. When Stefan Amaris seized Terra in December 2766, his forces captured three Avatar-class vessels undergoing refit at the Ian Cameron orbital yards. Only six Avatars survived the subsequent wars of liberation, five in SLDF service and one Rim Worlds Republic vessel recaptured at Nusakan in 2773. All six surviving hulls were selected for the Exodus fleet, their combination of substantial cargo capacity and multiple docking collars making them invaluable transports for the long journey into exile.</p><p>Upon reaching the Pentagon worlds, the Avatars were mothballed along with much of the Exodus fleet. The vessels remained in storage through the founding of the Clans and the conflicts of Operation KLONDIKE, though at least two hulls saw active service during that campaign in their original Avatar configuration. After the Pentagon worlds were pacified and Clan society stabilized, the dormant fleet was largely set aside as the Clans focused on ground-based military development.</p><p>The reactivation program began in the early thirty-first century as the Clans prepared for their long-anticipated invasion of the Inner Sphere. Clan technicians performed comprehensive upgrades to the surviving Avatar hulls, installing advanced armor plating, Clan-specification weapons systems, and enhanced electronics. The refitted vessels were redesignated as the Liberator-class, entering service around 3024. Multiple Clans received Liberators, reflecting the broad distribution of former SLDF assets during the original Pentagon settlement.</p><p>The invasion era and its aftermath took a steady toll on the small Liberator fleet. Three vessels were lost between 3060 and 3070, mirroring the broader attrition of irreplaceable former Star League WarShip designs across all Clans. Despite these losses, the class demonstrated remarkable staying power. Clan Wolf retained two Liberators through the Jihad and into the Dark Age, while Clan Coyote maintained a third through the Wars of Reaving despite the near-total collapse of Coyote naval power. The survival of these vessels more than a century after their Clan-era refit reinforced both the soundness of the original Avatar design and the quality of Clan engineering that gave these ancient hulls renewed purpose.</p>
</history>

